New Rules for the World Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Let us assume that the world's leading politicians would once again meet in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new world economic order.
Of course, they would primarily deal with today's problems: the crisis in the Eurozone, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, etc. However, addressing these issues would force the assembled leaders to go beyond them and reconsider the overall solidity of global economic arrangements.
Here are seven principles for global economic governance based on sound common sense, on which they might possibly agree.
(I discuss these in more detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. Markets must be deeply embedded in existing control systems.
The idea that markets can regulate themselves has suffered a fatal blow due to the recent financial crisis and should be buried forever.
Markets need other societal institutions that support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies that establish and enforce rules.
They depend on stabilization functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
They require political acceptance generated by redistributive taxation, safety nets, and social insurance.
And all of this applies equally to global markets.
2. For the foreseeable future, democratic governance will largely remain organized within national political communities.
The nation-state lives on, even if it may be somewhat weakened, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile love affair.
It is hardly to be expected that national governments will cede considerable control power to transnational institutions; moreover, a harmonization of rules would benefit nothing societies with different needs and preferences.
The European Union could be the only exception to this axiom, although its current crisis seems rather to confirm it.
Too often we waste international cooperation on overly ambitious goals. In the end, weak results emerge that represent the smallest common denominator between the major countries.
When international cooperation is "successful," it produces rules that are either toothless or reflect the preferences of the more powerful countries.
The Basel rules on capital requirements and the WTO rules on subsidies, intellectual property, and investment measures typify this kind of excessive ambition.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic procedures in our own countries, rather than breaking them apart.

3. Pluralistic Prosperity: Acknowledging that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best meet their needs.
The USA, Europe, and Japan have generated comparable prosperity in the long term.
Yet their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social safety nets, and financial systems differ significantly, and a sequence of these "models"—one different in each decade—is then presented as the great success to be emulated.
The most successful societies of the future will allow room for experiments and allow further evolution of their institutions.
A world economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will rather promote such experimental zeal and evolutionary development than suppress it.
4. Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may seem harmless.
But they carry powerful implications that collide with the prevailing opinion of globalization supporters.
One such implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the instruments available to shape and preserve their own institutions – in a word: to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries may maintain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards or rules protecting consumer health and safety – and that they may do so by erecting barriers at their borders, if trade demonstrably threatens domestic practices that enjoy broad public support.
If globalization advocates are right, calls for such protective measures will fail due to a lack of evidence or support.
If they are wrong, there is a safety valve so that conflicting values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of maintaining national regulations – can both receive due attention in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or in the financial sector to maintain values and rules in one's own country should not be confused with using them to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in these countries find unacceptable.
Equally, they should not allow the USA or the EU to use trade sanctions or other pressure measures to change labor market rules, environmental policy, or financial regulation in other countries.
Countries have a right to difference, not to forced convergence.

6. International economic agreements to regulate the interaction between national institutions: Relying on national states to provide the basic control functions of the world economy does not mean that we should do without international rules.
The Bretton Woods system finally also had clear rules, even if these were limited in scope and depth.
A complete free-for-all would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the world economy that help vehicles of different sizes, shapes, and speeds to pass each other, rather than prescribing an identical car or a uniform speed limit.
We should strive to achieve a maximum degree of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity in national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot claim the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What gives the aforementioned principles their attractiveness and legitimacy is that they are based on democratic consultation – where this really happens, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this framework collapses.
We can then no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
Other, less liberal rules must apply for undemocratic states.
These are the principles that the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
Most importantly, they must accept the ultimate paradox that each of these principles illustrates: globalization works best when it is not taken too far.
